Scope:
  For a BK state x, the diagnostic computes

    delta(x)=1+e(x)-o(x),
    rho(x)=delta(x)-indicator_(o(x)=0).

  It checks the component identity

    sum rho = positive-relations

  and solves the exact capacitated transport problem from -rho to +rho
  when endpoints are restricted by BK graph distance.  The displayed
  minimum radii are exact for these three components.  The promotion and
  dihedral lines are exact counterexamples to proving component positivity
  by summing independent canonical sweep cycles.  The radius computations
  are finite certificates, not a proof of a uniform radius theorem.

Bounded linear-radius sweep:
  ./analyze_su2_plucker_sr_parity gt-bk-radius 4 5 4 14

  progress factors=1 cases=10 cached_degrees=17
  progress factors=2 cases=64 cached_degrees=88
  progress factors=3 cases=233 cached_degrees=418
  progress factors=4 cases=572 cached_degrees=2727
  progress factors=5 cases=1001 cached_degrees=13101
  SU2_PLUCKER_GT_BK_RADIUS_PARITY cases=1001 \
    cached_degrees=13101 result=PASS

  Here the tested radius is N, the number of enlarged vertices including
  the exchange target.  PASS means that the exact weighted transport
  saturates every negative residual in every loaded BK component in the
  stated bounded domain.  This is evidence for Target 22F3C, not a proof
  of the uniform radius-N Hall inequality.

Deficit-gradient bounded sweep:
  ./analyze_su2_plucker_sr_parity \
    gt-bk-radius-deficit 4 5 4 14

  progress factors=1 cases=10 cached_degrees=17
  progress factors=2 cases=64 cached_degrees=88
  progress factors=3 cases=233 cached_degrees=418
  progress factors=4 cases=572 cached_degrees=2727
  progress factors=5 cases=1001 cached_degrees=13101
  SU2_PLUCKER_GT_BK_RADIUS_DEFICIT_PARITY cases=1001 \
    cached_degrees=13101 result=PASS

  A directed BK edge x -> y is permitted here only when

    max(0,-rho(y)) <= max(0,-rho(x)).

  Thus PASS verifies the weighted radius-N Hall transport with
  nonincreasing local deficit throughout the bounded domain.

Two-stage gradient bounded sweep:
  ./analyze_su2_plucker_sr_parity \
    gt-bk-radius-gradient 4 5 4 14

  progress factors=1 cases=10 cached_degrees=17
  progress factors=2 cases=64 cached_degrees=88
  progress factors=3 cases=233 cached_degrees=418
  progress factors=4 cases=572 cached_degrees=2727
  progress factors=5 cases=1001 cached_degrees=13101
  SU2_PLUCKER_GT_BK_RADIUS_GRADIENT_PARITY cases=1001 \
    cached_degrees=13101 result=PASS

  While q=max(0,-rho) is positive, a directed edge is permitted only when
  (q,o) is lexicographically nonincreasing.  At q=0, every edge which
  remains at q=0 is allowed.  This separates deficit descent from
  redistribution inside the zero-deficit reservoir.

Two-move local gradient sweep:
  ./analyze_su2_plucker_sr_parity \
    gt-bk-gradient-local 4 5 4 14

  progress factors=1 cases=10 cached_degrees=17
  progress factors=2 cases=64 cached_degrees=88
  progress factors=3 cases=233 cached_degrees=418
  progress factors=4 cases=572 cached_degrees=2727
  progress factors=5 cases=1001 cached_degrees=13101
  SU2_PLUCKER_GT_BK_GRADIENT_LOCAL_PARITY cases=1001 \
    cached_degrees=13101 result=PASS

  In addition to the two-stage Hall transport, this mode requires every
  q>0 state either to have a lexicographically lower (q,o) neighbor or to
  reach a state with such a neighbor by one constant-(q,o) BK edge.  The
  plateau swap and the lowering swap are additionally required to be
  adjacent generators.  Every visited BK state is also independently
  evaluated by the signed one-queue transfer of Lemma 22F3A1; the program
  aborts unless its unsigned and signed terminal counts equal respectively
  1+e+o and 1+e-o.

