  The q-o Lyapunov interval asks for a scalar lambda such that
  q(1+lambda o) is nonnegative and superharmonic at every negative state.
  The empty intervals in the two larger benchmarks rule out this scalar
  averaging shortcut.

Nonincreasing-odd counterexample:
  ./analyze_su2_plucker_sr_parity \
    gt-bk-radius-odd 4 5 4 14

  labels=[1,2,3,3,4] target=1 minus_mask=16 \
    odd_sources=6 odd_rank=4 positive_sources=3 \
    xor_demand=640 xor_capacity=628 result=FAIL

  Exact single-case comparison:

    demand=640 supply=2032
    nonincreasing_odd_flow=628
    nonincreasing_deficit_flow=640
    deficit_odd_gradient_flow=640
    radius_flows={1:12,2:64,3:320,4:528,5:632,6:640}
    minimum_radius=6

  Hence raw odd-cut count is not the correct monotone potential.  The local
  deficit survives this obstruction exactly.

Exact metric-XOR obstruction:
  For [1^-,1^-,2^+,2^+,3^+], target 1:

    xor_pairs=1848
    xor_pair_missing_within_N=392
    xor_pair_globally_absent=384
    negative_fibers=744
    xor_disconnected_negative_fibers=64
    metric_tree_relations=2192
    metric_tree_disconnected_fibers=64
    metric_tree_disconnected_profiles={(2,0):64}
    metric_tree_matching=2192
    metric_tree_target=2256

  For [2^+,2^+,3^-,4^+,5^+], target 2, loaded component:

    xor_pairs=1184
    xor_pair_missing_within_N=448
    xor_pair_globally_absent=448
    negative_fibers=872
    xor_disconnected_negative_fibers=320
    metric_tree_relations=1384
    metric_tree_disconnected_fibers=320
    metric_tree_disconnected_profiles={(2,0):320}
    metric_tree_matching=1384
    metric_tree_target=1704

  The metric-tree rule gives every odd-pair edge all positive resources in
  its own fibre and all resources in its XOR channel at BK distance at most
  N.  It chooses a minimum-distance spanning forest and computes an exact
  transversal matching.  The disconnected profiles show that every missing
  tree relation comes from a two-odd-cut, zero-positive fibre.  The globally
  absent counts prove that increasing the transport radius cannot repair
  the pairwise-XOR rule.

